questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot application experiences a gradual increase in Heap usage, eventually leading to `java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`. Analysis of the heap dump reveals millions of `byte[]` instances retained by `ThreadLocalMap` entries. You locate the following class used in a Spring MVC Interceptor:

java
@Component
public class UserContextInterceptor implements HandlerInterceptor {
    private static final ThreadLocal<UserContext> contextHolder = new ThreadLocal<>();

    @Override
    public boolean preHandle(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, Object handler) {
        UserContext context = extractContext(request);
        contextHolder.set(context);
        return true;
    }

    @Override
    public void afterCompletion(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, Object handler, Exception ex) {
        // Context is left as-is to avoid re-allocation overhead
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a microservice using Spring Data JPA and Hibernate experiences severe performance degradation and high memory usage. You observe that a transactional service method is fetching a lazy-loaded collection inside a parallel stream:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public void processPendingOrders(List<Long> orderIds) {
        orderIds.parallelStream().forEach(id -> {
            Order order = orderRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
            processItems(order.getItems()); // Lazy-loaded collection
        });
    }
}


This code occasionally throws `LazyInitializationException` and causes high JVM memory overhead due to duplicate entity allocations.
